he '''World Group''' was the highest level of [[Davis Cup]] competition in 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/draws-results/world-group.aspx#/1989|title=World Group 1989|publisher=DavisCup.com|accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref> The first-round losers went into the [[1989 Davis Cup World Group Qualifying Round|Davis Cup World Group Qualifying Round]], and the winners progressed to the quarterfinals and were guaranteed a World Group spot for [[1990 Davis Cup World Group|1990]].\n\n[[Germany Davis Cup team|West Germany]] won the title for a second consecutive year, defeating [[Sweden Davis Cup team|Sweden]] in the final, 3\u20132. The final was held at the [[Hanns-Martin-Schleyer-Halle|Schleyer-Halle]] in [[Stuttgart]], [[West Germany]], on 15\u201317 December.<ref name=\"WG Final\" /> It was the West Germany team's 2nd Davis Cup title overall.\n\n==Participating teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:98%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=4|Participating teams\n|-\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|AUS}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|AUT}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|TCH}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|DEN}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|FRA}}\n!{{davis-big|INA}}\n!{{davis-big|ISR}}\n!{{davis-big|ITA}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|MEX}}\n!{{davis-big|PAR|1988}}\n!{{davis-big|URS}}\n!{{davis-big|ESP}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|SWE}}\n!{{davis-big|USA}}\n!{{davis-big|FRG}}\n!{{davis-big|YUG}}\n|}\n\n==Draw==\n{{DCWorld\n| RD1-date=3\u20135 February\n| RD2-date=7\u20139 April\n| RD3-date=21\u201323 July\n| RD4-date=15\u201317 December\n\n| RD1T1-loc=[[Malm\u00f6]], [[Sweden]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed1= | RD1-team1={{davis|SWE}} | RD1-score1=4\n| RD1-seed2= | RD1-team2={{davis|ITA}} | RD1-score2=1\n\n| RD1T2-loc=[[Vienna]], [[Austria]] (indoor clay)\n| RD1-seed3= | RD1-team3={{davis|AUS}} | RD1-score3=0\n| RD1-seed4= | RD1-team4={{davis|AUT}} | RD1-score4=5\n\n| RD1T3-loc=[[Belgrade]], [[Yugoslavia]] (indoor clay)\n| RD1-seed5= | RD1-team5={{davis|YUG}} | RD1-score5=4\n| RD1-seed6= | RD1-team6={{davis|DEN}} | RD1-score