eam|West Germany]] won the title, defeating the defending champions [[Sweden Davis Cup team|Sweden]] in the final, 4\u20131. The final was held at the [[Scandinavium]] in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]], from 16 to 18 December.<ref name=\"WG Final\" /> It was the West German team's first Davis Cup title (having previously come runner-up in [[1970 Davis Cup|1970]] and [[1985 Davis Cup|1985]]), becoming the ninth nation to win the Davis Cup.\n\n==Participating teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:98%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=4| Participating teams\n|-\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|AUS}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|BRA|1968}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|TCH}}\n!width=25%|{{davis-big|DEN}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|FRA}}\n!{{davis-big|IND}}\n!{{davis-big|ISR}}\n!{{davis-big|ITA}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|MEX}}\n!{{davis-big|NZL}}\n!{{davis-big|PAR|1988}}\n!{{davis-big|ESP}}\n|-\n!{{davis-big|SWE}}\n!{{davis-big|SUI}}\n!{{davis-big|FRG}}\n!{{davis-big|YUG}}\n|}\n\n===Draw===\n{{DCWorld\n| RD1-date=5\u20137 February\n| RD2-date=8\u201310 April\n| RD3-date=22\u201324 July\n| RD4-date=16\u201318 December\n\n| RD1T1-loc=[[G\u00e4vle]], [[Sweden]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed1= | RD1-team1={{davis|SWE}} | RD1-score1=5\n| RD1-seed2= | RD1-team2={{davis|NZL}} | RD1-score2=0\n\n| RD1T2-loc=[[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed3= | RD1-team3={{davis|TCH}} | RD1-score3=5\n| RD1-seed4= | RD1-team4={{davis|PAR|1988}} | RD1-score4=0\n\n| RD1T3-loc=[[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]] (clay)\n| RD1-seed5= | RD1-team5={{davis|AUS}} | RD1-score5=3\n| RD1-seed6= | RD1-team6={{davis|MEX}} | RD1-score6=2\n\n| RD1T4-loc=[[Basel]], [[Switzerland]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed7= | RD1-team7={{davis|FRA}} | RD1-score7=4\n| RD1-seed8= | RD1-team8={{davis|SUI}} | RD1-score8=1\n\n| RD1T5-loc=[[Essen]], [[West Germany]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed9= | RD1-team9={{davis|BRA|1968}} | RD1-score9=0\n| RD1-seed10= | RD1-team10={{davis|FRG}} | RD1-score10=5\n\n| RD1T6-loc=[[Aarhus]], [[Denmark]] (indoor carpet)\n| RD1-seed11=